  "issue_title": "Add Context.Delete / Context.Remove method for safe key deletion",
  "issue_body": "### Feature Description\n\nSummary\n\nAdd a thread-safe Delete (or Remove) method to *gin.Context that allows safely deleting a key from Context.Keys without directly manipulating the underlying map.\n\nMotivation\n\nCurrently, *gin.Context exposes c.Keys (a map[string]any) publicly, but the only safe accessors provided are Get, Set, and MustGet.\nThese methods use an internal sync.RWMutex to guard concurrent access to c.Keys.\n\nHowever, developers sometimes need to remove temporary request-scoped values (e.g., authentication tokens, debug flags, or per-request state) after use.\nAt the moment, there is no supported API for this. The only way is:\n```\ndelete(c.Keys, \"temp\")\n```\n\nThis bypasses the mutex protection and can easily cause: `fatal error: concurrent map read and map write`\n\nespecially when multiple middlewares or goroutines call Get/Set concurrently on the same context.\n\nThis limitation leads to race conditions or unsafe code patterns, as the mutex cannot be used externally.\n\n\nProposed Solution\n\nAdd a safe Delete method to *gin.Context, similar to Get and Set, that uses the same internal lock.\n\nExample API:\n\n```\n// Delete removes a key from the context safely.\nfunc (c *Context) Delete(key string) {\n    c.mu.Lock()\n    defer c.mu.Unlock()\n    if c.Keys != nil {\n        delete(c.Keys, key)\n    }\n}\n```\n\n\nThis is consistent with existing Gin methods:\n - Uses the same mu protecting Keys.\n - No external API changes or breaking behavior.\n - Keeps developer ergonomics consistent with Set/Get.\n",
